The heatmap graph shows genes that are expressed most differentially. Clustering was performed to visualize the correlations among the replicates and varying sample conditions. The heatmap displays the patterns of upregulated (red signal) and downregulated (green signal) genes of these CBNs-treated samples and the control sample (Fig. 6
                        ). According to the heatmap, the genetic profiles of SW- and Gra-treated samples seemed closer to the control group compared to the other examined CBNs (Fig. 6). Notably, ND-treated sample exhibited a significantly different genetic pattern compared to control and other groups (Fig. 6), which is consistent with the PCA plot analysis (Fig. 5). The numbers of differentially expressed genes (DEGs) of each treatment samples are listed in Table 1
                        , and among these samples, the ND-treated sample upregulated and downregulated over one thousand genes each.

Gene Ontology (GO) analysis was further performed to investigate the biological effects ND caused in human cells. A list of top enrichment GO biological processes are shown in Table 2
                        , including cell cycle and autophagy, etc., which is compatible with results from our cellular and molecular experiments (Fig. 3 and Fig. 4). Among the list, the cell cycle pathway is highlighted on the top, containing 58 regulated genes (Table 2). In order to better understand the impacts of these regulations at the functional protein level, we further analyze the listed 58 molecules by protein-protein interaction software, STRING (Version 12.0). With setting as no >50 interactors, protein-protein associations are indicated by connecting colors of lines, indicating the type of evidenced interaction, including databases, experiments, co-expression, gene fusion, etc., and then the network is clustered by Markov Cluster Algorithm (MCL clustering) through STRING software (Fig. 8
                        ).
